`crates/ctx-cage` is a standalone crate that runs an autonomous agent inside an offline bwrap sandbox, with the host as sole arbiter of egress and tool access. Depending on it means depending on the three binaries it builds — `ctx-cage`, `ctx-run`, and `ctx_cage_client` — not on any internal module surface, which is intentionally partitioned (argv construction, wire protocol, proxying, runtime resolution) and documented per-submodule.

The crate has three parts: `Cargo.toml` declares the package/binary layout, `src/` is the entire implementation (sandbox setup, two host↔cage boundaries — raw proxy vs. allowlisted broker — and the shared `CageError` type), and `assets/` holds the static payloads (`cage-nsswitch.conf`, `cage-rules.md`) that `src/` compiles in and injects at runtime. `tests/` exercises `src/`'s subsystems largely in isolation, with its own duplicated knowledge of `src/`'s constants and shapes (`BwrapConfig`, `Cli`/`Mode`, proxy header rules) that must track any renaming there.

The cross-cutting coupling to know before editing: `assets/cage-rules.md` must stay synchronized with whatever tool names and mount/network setup `src/` actually implements (e.g. `ctx-verify`, `.context/`, available NSS sockets), and `src/lib.rs`'s documented sandbox guarantees (workspace RW at real path, `.env`/`.git/config` masked, offline except proxy socket, system prompt injection) are binding on both the bwrap builders and `runtime.rs` — any new launcher path or test fixture must preserve them rather than reinvent.

No `intent.md` exists for this directory, so no divergence can be assessed.